<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910926-0173</DOCNO><DOCID>910926-0173.</DOCID><HL>   Chevron Splits   Biggest Unit,   Shifts Managers   ----   By Richard Turner   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>09/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C11</SO><CO>   CHV</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>MANAGEMENT ISSUES (MNT)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   SAN FRANCISCO -- Chevron Corp. said it split its largestunit into two separate companies, and announced several majorexecutive changes.   Chevron USA will be split into Chevron USA Production Co.,for exploration and production activities, and Chevron USAProducts Co., for refining and marketing. W.J. Price, 60years old, will retire Jan. 1 as president of Chevron USA,and from the parent's executive committee. Mr. Price servedat Chevron for 38 years.</LP><TEXT>   Succeeding Mr. Price will be Raymond E. Galvin, 59, whowill be president of the production unit, and David R. Hoyer,60, who will be president of the products unit. Both men arecurrently senior vice presidents of Chevron USA.   A company spokesman said the changes wouldn't result inany work force reductions, and that reallocation of personnelwas being studied for those departments, such as legal, whichwould be affected. But the company has long divided manyfunctions according to the &quot;upstream&quot; and &quot;downstream&quot; partsof its business, which correspond to the two new units.   &quot;This reorganization is consistent with many of the otherchanges we've made at Chevron in recent years,&quot; ChevronChairman Kenneth T. Derr in a statement. &quot;We have beendecentralizing our operations and establishing strategicbusiness units, delegating authority to lower levels,eliminating layers of management and increasing our customerfocus throughout our organization.&quot;   David J. O'Reilly, 44, senior vice president of Chevron'schemical unit, was named a vice president of the parent,responsible for strategic planning, beginning Oct. 1. Hebecomes one of 18 corporate vice presidents, a number thatwill remain the same because Mr. Price served as one.   Mr. O'Reilly will be succeeded at the chemical unit byDavid W. Callahan, 48, now president of Chevron's WarrenPetroleum unit, a wholesale marketer of natural gas liquids.Peter J. Robertson, 44, now vice president of finance forChevron USA, will succeed Mr. Callahan.   Paul R. Larson, 61, vice president of manufacturing forChevron USA, and Bruce D. Frolich, 51, vice president ofsupply and distribution, will assume each other'sresponsibilities Nov. 1 at the new Chevron USA Products Co.,which will be renamed Chevron USA Refining.   A. Don Cornwell, 54, will become vice president offinance, treasurer and secretary of Chevron Chemical,succeeding James R. Dixon, 62, who is retiring.</TEXT></DOC>